{{Infobox Congressman |name= Melvin Clark George |image name=Melvin Clark George.jpg |state1= [[Oregon]] |district1 = {{ushr|Oregon|AL|At-large}} |party= [[Republican Party (United States)|Republican]] |term_start1 = March 4, 1881 |term_end1 = March 3, 1885 |preceded1= [[John Whiteaker]] |succeeded1= [[Binger Hermann]] |office2 = Member of the [[Oregon Senate]] |term_start2 = 1876 |term_end2 = 1880 |birth_date= May 13, 1849 |birth_place= [[Caldwell, Ohio]] |death_date= February 22, 1933 (aged 83) |death_place=[[Portland, Oregon]] |spouse=Mary Eckler |current occupation= }} '''Melvin Clark''' (or ''Clarke'') '''George''' (May 13, 1849 – February 22, 1933) was a [[United States House of Representatives|U.S. Representative]] from [[Oregon]].
==Early life== He was born near [[Caldwell, Ohio]] to Presley and Mahala Nickerson George.<ref name=Corning>{{cite book|last=Corning|first=Howard M|title=Dictionary of Oregon History|publisher=Binfords & Mort Publishing|year=1956}}</ref> He moved with his parents over the [[Oregon Trail]] in 1851 and settled on a homestead near [[Lebanon, Oregon|Lebanon]] in [[Linn County, Oregon]]. In Oregon he attended country schools, then [[Santiam Academy]], and finally [[Willamette University]] in [[Salem, Oregon|Salem]].
He served as principal of the [[Albany, Oregon|Albany]] schools and the Jefferson Institute in what would become [[Jefferson, Oregon|Jefferson]]. He studied law, and was [[Admission to the bar in the United States|admitted to the bar]] and commenced practice in [[Portland, Oregon|Portland]] in 1875.<ref name=Corning/><ref name=bioguide>{{cite web|title=Biographical Directory of the United States Congress| publisher = U.S. Government Printing Office | url = http://bioguide.congress.gov/scripts/biodisplay.pl?index=G000128| accessdate = 2008-05-14}}</ref>
In 1873, he married Mary Eckler, with whom he had three children.<ref name=Corning/><ref name=ons>{{cite journal|title=Oregon Native Son|volume=1|issue=2|date=June 1899|page=115|publisher=Portland, Oregon Native Son Pub. Co|url=http://ftp.rootsweb.ancestry.com/pub/usgenweb/or/bios/george-mc.txt?cj=1&o_xid=0002530104&o_lid=0002530104|format= &ndash; <sup>[https://scholar.google.co.uk/scholar?hl=en&lr=&q=intitle%3AOregon+Native+Son&as_publication=&as_ylo=1899&as_yhi=1899&btnG=Search Scholar search]</sup>}} {{dead link|date=April 2009}}</ref>
==Political career== George served as member of the [[Oregon State Senate]] from [[Multnomah County, Oregon|Multnomah County]] from 1876 to 1880.<ref name=Corning/><ref name=bioguide/> In 1880, he was elected as a [[Republican Party (United States)|Republican]] to [[Oregon's At-large congressional district]] in the [[United States House of Representatives]], defeating incumbent [[John Whiteaker]] by 1,397 votes.<ref name=bioguide/><ref name=kincaid>{{cite book|title=Biennial Report of the Secretary of State of the State of Oregon|last=Kincaid|first=H. R.|authorlink=Harrison R. Kincaid|year=1899|publisher=W. H. Leeds|location=[[Salem, Oregon]]|page=235|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=K3A4AAAAMAAJ&pg=RA3-PA23}}</ref> In 1882, he defeated Democrat [[William D. Fenton]] by 3,365 votes to become the first Oregon congressman to be re-elected to a second term.<ref name=kincaid/> During his term in Congress, George promoted construction of jetties at the mouth of the [[Columbia River]].<ref name=Corning/> He did not seek a third term in 1884.<ref name=bioguide/>
==After Congress== Following his term in Congress, George served as a professor of [[medical jurisprudence]] at Willamette University from 1885 to 1889.<ref name=Corning/> He served on the Portland school board, and then in 1891, was appointed chairman of the Portland bridge commission, which sought to provide free bridges throughout the city.<ref name=Corning/><ref name=bioguide/><ref name=ons/> In this capacity, George oversaw the construction of the [[Burnside Bridge]]. George Park in the [[St. Johns, Portland, Oregon|St. Johns]] neighborhood of Portland is named in his honor.<ref name=ppr>{{cite web|url=http://www.portlandonline.com/parks/finder/index.cfm?action=ViewPark&PropertyID=148|publisher=Portland Parks and Recreation|title=George Park|accessdate=2008-05-14}}</ref>
George also served as a Multnomah circuit court judge from 1897 to 1905, and then practiced law in Portland until his death in Portland on February 22, 1933. He is interred at [[Lone Fir Cemetery (Portland, Oregon)|Lone Fir Cemetery]].<ref name=bioguide/>
